    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
Appendix testis
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ASAP [F]</title>
    <created>20161110T145312Z</created>
    <updated>20241204T021636Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>atypical small acinar proliferation</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows prostatic tissue with tiny aggregates of atypical acini.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, there is focal loss of p63 and 34BE12-positive basal cells in the periphery of these atypical glands. No immunoreactivity for AMACR is noted in these atypical acini. These foci represent atypical small acinar proliferation (ASAP). Re-biopsy is recommended.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>benign prostatic tissue with IHC_form</title>
    <created>20191213T090014Z</created>
    <updated>20260330T020905Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>1.Prostate, right, TRUS-P biopsy --- Benign prostatic  tissue.</div><div>2.Prostate, left, TRUS-P biopsy --- benign prostatic tissue.</div><div><br/></div><div>GROSS DESCRIPTION:</div><div>1.The specimen #1 (right) submitted consists of _ pieces of tissue measuring up to _ cm, fixed in formalin. All for section and labeled as A.  </div><div>2.The specimen #2 (left) submitted consists of _ pieces of tissue measuring up to _ cm in size, fixed in formalin. All for section and labeled as B.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows prostatic tissue. Focal aggregate of small acini is seen. Immunohistochemically, basal cells surrounding the glands are highlighted by p63 and 34betaE12 immunostains. These findings indicate a benign process without evidence of malignancy.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BPH (nodular hyperplasia)</title>
    <created>20170117T010027Z</created>
    <updated>20241206T015406Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Prostate gland, TURP ---  nodular hyperplasia</div><div><br/></div><div>Gross description:</div><div>The specimen consists of multiple pieces of tissue measuring __ gm in total.</div><div><br/></div><div>All for section.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Nodular hyperplasia characterized by both glandular and fibromuscular stromal hyperplasia is seen.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BPH (nodular hyperplasia)  with IHC</title>
    <created>20170117T010027Z</created>
    <updated>20231009T020902Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Nodular hyperplasia.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div>Nodular hyperplasia characterized by both glandular and fibromuscular stromal hyperplasia is seen. F<span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">ocal aggregates of </span><span style="line-height: 1.45;">small acini are seen. </span></div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, basal cells surrounding the glands <span style="line-height: 1.45;">are highlighted by p63 and 34betaE12 immunostains. No </span><span style="line-height: 1.45;">immunoreactivity for AMACR is noted in these acini. These</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">findings indicate a benign process without evidence of </span><span style="line-height: 1.45;">malignancy.</span></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Aggregate of small acini of similar sizes are noted, in which prostatic acinar adenocarcinoma was included into differential diagnoses, and cannot be excluded solely on HE-stained section. A panel of AMACR, p63 and 34betaE12 were perfromed to exclude malignancy.  Thank you.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Nodular hyperplasia characterized by both glandular and fibromuscular stromal hyperplasia is seen.</div><div>Aggregate of small acini of similar sizes are noted, in which prostatic acinar adenocarcinoma cannot be excluded on H&amp;E section. AMACR is weakly and focally positive. P63 and 34betaE12 show preserved basal cells, excluding malignancy. </div></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
