  <note>
    <title>Ductal adenocarcinoma, prostate</title>
    <created>20161110T145325Z</created>
    <updated>20161110T145337Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>Both right and left prostatic glands reveal ductal adenocarcinoma _with focal presence of comedo necrosis. Larger surgical specimen is suggested for a definite subtyping.</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Endothelial adrenal cyst</title>
    <created>20170728T025832Z</created>
    <updated>20170728T025842Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>It shows adrenal gland tissue with a demarcated cystic lesion lined by bland-looking,</div><div>flattened cells. Dystrophic calcifications are seen in the cystic wall. By</div><div>immunohistochemistry, the lining cells are positive for CD31 and</div><div>D2-40 but not AE1/AE3, consistent with the diagnosis.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20221128T093939Z</created>
    <updated>20221128T094001Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>fibroepithelial polyp.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The polypoid tissue is lined by an intact urothelium and its stroma is made up of loose collagen.        </div><div>Immunohistochemically, the urothelium is negative for CK20 except the umbrella cells. P53 shows no overexpression.</div><div>No malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Fourniers gangrene</title>
    <created>20170606T064051Z</created>
    <updated>20180823T045956Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Necrotizing inflammation, consistent with Fourniers gangrene</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show soft tissue revealing extensive necrotizing inflammation with necrotic debris and mixed inflammatory cells. No malignancy is observed.<br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>TESTIS: Sections of the testis reveal congestion with focal atrophy of seminiferous tubules. Necrotizing inflammation is seen within tunica albuginea and tunica vaginalis. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>HGPIN</title>
    <created>20170509T052504Z</created>
    <updated>20181210T065234Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>It shows prostatic tissue strips with focal high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia, which shows bridging or tufting of epithelial cells bearing conspicuous nucleoli and being immunoreactive to p504s with surrounding basal cells highlighted by p63 and HMWCK (34βE12) immunostains. Close follow-up with repeated biopsy is highly recommended.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Intraductal carcinoma of the prostate; see comment.</title>
    <created>20210528T015119Z</created>
    <updated>20210528T015710Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Comment: Intraductal carcinoma is usually associated with high-grade invasive cancer. </div><div>Re-biopsy is suggested. </div><hr/><div>Thought whether to proceed directly to definitve therapy versus do a repeat biopsy as our recommendation to discover invasive (usually high-grade cancer) has been debated. </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>inverted PUNLMP</title>
    <created>20230302T045158Z</created>
    <updated>20230302T045226Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Inverted papillary urothelial neoplasm of low malignant potential (inverted PUNLMP).</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDINGS:</div><div>Sections show mostly inverted papilloma, characterized by anastomosing urothelial cords of normal thickness and preserved polarity, growing in an endophytic pattern from the normal overlying urothelium, invaginating into the lamina propria. However, focal areas show thickening of the urothelium, with mild cellular and nuclear enlargement and without variation in nuclear size.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the urothelial cells are negative for CK20. No overexpression of p53 is seen. The Ki67 proliferation index shows no siginificant increase. The pathologic findings are consistent with inverted PUNLMP.</div><div>Chips of benign prostatic tissue is also seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20221212T023456Z</created>
    <updated>20221212T023510Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Inverted urothelial papilloma.<br/></div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDINGS:</div><div>Section shosws downward growing nests and trabeculae of urothelial cells, with pseudoglandular spaces and peripheral palisading. The urothelial cells show spindled appearance with little intervening stroma. Overlying surface urothelium is unremarkable.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Malakoplakia</title>
    <created>20170307T070010Z</created>
    <updated>20251203T060602Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Malakoplakia.</div><div>Microscopic description: </div><div>Sections show soft tissue lined by urothelium accompanied by accumulation of foamy histiocytes (von Hansemann's histiocytes) containing Michaelis-Gutmann bodies in the subepeithelial tissue.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the histiocytes are highlighted by CD68. The urothelium is positive for CK7 but not CK20.</div><div><br/></div><div>Stainings for PAS and GMS highlight the Michaelis-Gutmann bodies, consistent with the diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Necrosis (2nd look)</title>
    <created>20170104T061706Z</created>
    <updated>20170104T061730Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><ol><li><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-size: small; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); float: none; display: inline !important;"> <span style="font-size: 12px;">Section shows urinary bladder with necrosis, fibrosis and scattered mixed inflammatory cells.</span></span></li><li><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">The base is free of tumor.</span></span></span></li></ol></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20220902T042819Z</created>
    <updated>20220902T042842Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>nephrogenic adenoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDINGS:</div><div>Section shows tubules lined by cuboidal or hobnail cells in the stroma. Focally increased Ki67 index is noted.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the lining epithelium of tubules is positive for PAX8, AMACR and AE1/AE3 but not CK20. P53 shows no overexpression.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
