  <note>
    <title>TURBT</title>
    <created>20191219T030931Z</created>
    <updated>20230612T015443Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-url>file:///C:\Users\h3d0\Desktop\Form_Huang\10-urinary%20bladder%20cancer%20checklist%20-%20TURBT.doc</source-url>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Urinary bladder, status post-TUR-BT--- Infiltrating urothelial carcinoma, high grade (pT)</div><div><br clear="none" /></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>Histologic type: Infiltrating urothelial carcinoma</div><div>Histologic grade: High grade</div><div>Extent of invasion:</div><div>  Depth of invasion: ________</div><div>  Prostatic urethra: Free</div><div>  Distal end of right ureter: Free</div><div>pTa: Papillary noninvasive carcinoma</div><div>pTis: Urothelial carcinoma in situ (flat tumor)</div><div>pT1: Tumor invades lamina propria (subepithelial connective tissue)</div><div>pT2: Tumor invades the muscularis</div><div>pT2a: Tumor invades superficial muscularis propria (inner half)</div><div>pT2b: Tumor invades deep muscularis propria (outer half)</div><div>pT3: Tumor invades perivesical soft tissue</div><div>pT3a: Tumor invades perivesical soft tissue microscopically</div><div>pT3b: Tumor invades perivesical soft tissue macroscopically (extravesical mass)</div><div>pT4: Extravesical tumor directly invades any of the following: prostatic stroma, seminal vesicles, uterus, vagina, pelvic wall, abdominal wall</div><div>pT4a: Extravesical tumor directly invades prostatic stroma, seminal vesicles, uterus, or vagina</div><div>pT4b: Extravesical tumor invades pelvic wall or abdominal wall</div><div>"UC with muscle invasion, indeterminate for type of muscle invasion"</div><div>Urothelial carcinoma in situ: present / absent</div><div>Peritumoral lymphovascular invasion: Present / Absent</div><div>Perineural invasion: Present / Absent</div><div>Margin:</div><div>Tumor base: Free of tumor   Presence of tumor element, with / without finding of muscular invasion</div><div>Muscularis propria:  __ Present;   __ Absent</div><div>Lymph nodes: not assessed</div><div>Immunohistochemical study:</div><div>pTNM:  pT___N___ (AJCC cancer staging system, 8th edition)</div><div style="margin-top: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em;">TNM descriptors: ___y(posttherapy); ___r(retreatment or recurrence); ___a(autopsy); ___m(multiple);  <br clear="none" /></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>UC</title>
    <created>20161205T070456Z</created>
    <updated>20231009T011956Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Urothelial carcinoma, invasive</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows scanty and crushed tissue with atypical urothelial cells revealing nuclear pleomorphsm and hyperchromatism. Necrosis is also seen.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for CK7 and CK20, supporting the diagnosis and also highlighting the invasive tumor nests.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Urothelial carcinoma, invasive</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows neoplastic urothelial cells bearing high-grade nuclei arranged in papillary patterns with stromal invasion.</div><div><br/></div><div>Section shows tiny tissue fragments with predominant necrosis. A few small foci of urothelium are seen, revealing nuclear pleomorphsm and hyperchromatism. No invasive foci are identified in this specimen.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>UCIS</title>
    <created>20160921T074630Z</created>
    <updated>20240923T061747Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>urothelial carcinoma in situ.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div>Section shows fibroepithelial tissue with partially covering urothelial cells revealing enlarged and hyperchromatic nuclei with loss of polarity. No stromal invasion is discerned.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Urology</title>
    <created>20140911T041101Z</created>
    <updated>20231124T042815Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="color: rgb(153, 51, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;"><br clear="none" /></span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(153, 51, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Papillary urothelial neoplasm of low malignant potential 性質</span></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Section shows orderly arrangement of proliferating urothelial cells in papillary structures with minimal to absent architectural or cytologic atypia.<br clear="none" />
Immunoahistochemically, the urothelial cells express CK7 and CK20, consistent with the diagnosis.<br clear="none" /></span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(153, 51, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Von Brunn nest</span><br clear="none" /></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Section shows well-circumscribed nests of urothelial cells budding from the overlying</span><br clear="none" /><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">epithelium in the lamina propria. No malignancy is observed.</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(153, 51, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Urothelial carcinoma, biopsy</span></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><br clear="none" /></div><div><br/></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><br clear="none" /></div><div><span style="color: rgb(153, 51, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Cystitis cystica</span></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Section shows fibroepithelial tissue focally lined by benign urothelium accompanied by cystically dilated lumun in the subepithelial tissue.<br clear="none" /><br clear="none" />
Immunohistochemially, the urothelial cells are positive for CK7. Umbrella cells are<br clear="none" />
positive for CK20. No malignancy is observed.</span></div><div><br/></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;"><br clear="none" /></span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;"><br clear="none" /></span></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;"><br clear="none" /></span></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><br clear="none" /></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;"><span style="color: rgb(255, 0, 255);">KIDNEY</span></span></div><div><br clear="none" /></div><div><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;"><br clear="none" /></span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(153, 51, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Simple cyst</span></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Section shows a cystic lesion with thin fibrous wall, focally lined by flattened epithelial cells. No malignancy is observed.</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(153, 51, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Atrophy</span><br clear="none" /></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Sections show renal parenchyma exhibiting extensive glomerulosclerosis and tubular thyroidization, accompanied by multiple cysts lined by bland-looking, flattened or cuboidal epithelium. The ureter is unremarkable.</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(153, 51, 0); font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">RCC</span></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;">Sections show a tumor composed of clear cells with distinct cell membrane, separated by delicate vascular network arranged in nesting and (focal papillary patterns.)</span></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-family: &quot;times new roman&quot;, times, serif;"><br clear="none" /></span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Urothelial dysplasia</title>
    <created>20161005T074624Z</created>
    <updated>20241227T080418Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Urothelial dysplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows urothelial dysplasia in which appreciable cytologic atypia and architectural changes are present but not enough to classify it as carcinoma in situ.</div><div>Staining for CK20 is negative. P53 shows no overexpression.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20201203T100454Z</created>
    <updated>20251015T055318Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Urothelial dysplasia with early papillary formation.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDINGS:</div><div>Section shows urothelial dysplasia in which appreciable</div><div>cytologic atypia and architectural changes are present but</div><div>not enough to classify it as carcinoma in situ. Early</div><div>papillary formation is seen.</div><div>Staining for CK20 is negative. P53 is focally positive.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Urothelial papilloma</title>
    <created>20260408T030910Z</created>
    <updated>20260408T031014Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Urothelial papilloma.</div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDINGS:</div><div>The section shows slender fibrovascular cores lined by normal urothelium with prominent umbrella cell layer highlighted by CK20. P53 shows wild type staining.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>varicocele</title>
